## Integration contract

How downstream / external consumers integrate with this project — the public surface they depend on (install steps, entry points, exported API, expected paths, env contract). Keep it aligned with the README install instructions: `pm-architect` (A4) cross-checks this section against them, and a diverging description is a self-inflicted finding. Mark `N/A — <reason>` for projects with no external integration surface.

- <e.g., "Installed via `pip install <pkg>`; entry point `<pkg>.run(config)`; reads config from `$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/<pkg>/config.toml`.">

## Behavioral contract (taxonomies & invariants)

The single home for this project's technical taxonomies and domain invariants — the machine-level facts that other docs reference but must never restate. This is **not** the integration surface above (that is *how* consumers integrate); this is *what values are legal and what must always hold*. Status enumerations, topic / ID / name grammars, QoS levels, retain semantics, reachability and ordering rules, state-machine transitions, numeric ranges and units all live here, stated once. `docs/user-journeys.md` and the contracts reference this section by name instead of copying identifiers — that move-not-copy discipline is what stops the classic drift ("6 statuses in the docs, 7 in the code"). Mark `N/A — <reason>` for projects with no taxonomies or format invariants (e.g. "N/A — no enumerations, identifier grammars, or transport-level invariants; all values are free-form user text").

Example — a status enumeration:

| Status | Meaning | Allowed next |
|---|---|---|
| `pending` | created, not yet processed | `active`, `cancelled` |
| `active` | in progress | `done`, `failed` |
| `done` | terminal success | — |

Example — an identifier grammar and a transport invariant:

- **Export ID grammar:** `export_<8-hex>` — lowercase hex, exactly 8 chars; generated server-side, never user-supplied.
- **Reachability:** a record is observable by a consumer only after its `active` transition has been published; consumers must tolerate the `pending` state never being visible.

### System invariants

The single index / entry point for this project's cross-cutting **system invariants** — the rules that must always hold across the whole system, gathered in one list so a top-down reader finds them once instead of three partial lists keyed differently. Each invariant is listed **by reference to its single home**, never restated:

- **inline** here, when the Behavioral contract is itself the home (a format / taxonomy / transport invariant it already states above — name it and let the statement above carry the rule);
- **by `SCn` ID**, when the invariant is enforced as a security constraint (the rule text stays in `## Security constraints` — reference the ID with a short human hint, exactly the threat → constraint Mitigation pattern; never copy the rule text down here);
- **by journey name**, when it is a journey-level precondition (the rule lives in that journey's `**Invariants:**` block in `docs/user-journeys.md` — name the journey, do not restate the precondition).

Reference-don't-duplicate, one-way-by-ID — the same discipline as threat → constraint: the index points *out* at each home, the home keeps **no back-link** to the index, and **no rule text is duplicated** (the only cross-doc datum is the `SCn` ID or the journey name). Mark `N/A — <reason>` for projects with no cross-cutting system invariants (e.g. "N/A — no cross-cutting invariants beyond the taxonomies above").

Example — a System-invariants index:

- **Reachability:** a record is observable only after its `active` transition is published — stated inline above (Behavioral contract is the home).
- **One commissioning window at a time:** enforced by whichever `SCn` you assigned this rule in your own `## Security constraints` (reference that ID here — e.g. `SC3` — never restate the rule text).
- **Pre-paired controller:** the *Commission a device* journey requires a paired controller before any device write (see `docs/user-journeys.md`).

## State model

The single home for this project's **state machine / protocol** — a states×transitions table plus the triggers/debounce that drive each edge, so a reader finds the lifecycle in one place instead of reverse-engineering it from prose. This section is for a project whose **core is a state machine / protocol** — a status ladder with defined transitions, a named-state lifecycle plus the events that move between states, or a wire/connection protocol with message/connection states. **Column-level ownership keeps this from restating the enum:** the **`## Behavioral contract` status enum owns the value set** — which states exist and what each means — and the table's State column is a *reference into* that enum (the source of truth for "is `failed` a legal state?"), never an independent re-declaration. The table's **own new datum is the transitions and their triggers** — the edges, with the *why/when* (event, condition, debounce) the enum's terse "Allowed next" does not capture; they live nowhere else. **Reference the enum, add the edges, never re-declare or re-mean a state here.** Reference the existing prose for the "why" justification rather than re-deriving it. A transition / trigger / debounce you cannot determine without real system knowledge is `[?]` for the PM to confirm — **never invent an edge** (the same "never invent to fill" discipline as the Behavioral contract; never reverse-engineer the model from code). Mark `N/A — <reason>` for a project whose core is not a state machine / protocol (the common case — this section is born `N/A`, like every other conditional section).

Example — a states×transitions table (states referenced from the `## Behavioral contract` enum above; only the edges and triggers are new here):

| State | Allowed transitions → | Trigger / event | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `pending` | `active`, `failed` | worker leases the record / admission check rejects | initial state on creation |
| `active` | `done`, `failed` | processing completes / processing errors | — |
| `done` | — | — | terminal success |
| `failed` | `active` | operator requeues for retry | terminal unless explicitly retried |

Triggers / debounce:

- <e.g., "`pending → active`: when a worker leases the record; the lease is the trigger, not a timer.">
- <e.g., "`active → failed`: on the first unrecoverable processing error; `failed → active` only on an explicit operator retry.">

## Release flow

How a commit becomes a published release. Keep it aligned with the CI definition: `pm-architect` (A4) cross-checks this section against `.github/workflows/auto-tag.yml` (or the equivalent CI workflow). Mark `N/A — <reason>` for projects with no automated release.

- <e.g., "Feature branch → PR → squash-merge to main → CI reads top CHANGELOG entry → tags `v<VERSION>` and publishes a GitHub Release.">

## Security constraints

The enforceable implementation rules — the **rule layer**. On a security-bearing project (one with `docs/threat-model.md`) each rule carries a stable `SCn` ID so the threat-model's Threats-table Mitigation column can reference it (`threat → constraint`, one-way, by ID — no rule text is duplicated into the threat-model). IDs are assigned once and never renumbered; a new rule gets the next free `SCn`.

- **SC1** — <e.g., "Passwords: bcrypt min cost 12, never stored plain, never logged">
- **SC2** — <e.g., "User input: validated and sanitized before any DB query or shell invocation (parameterized queries)">
- **SC3** — <e.g., "API keys: env vars only, never in source, never in response bodies or headers">
- **SC4** — <e.g., "Tokens: short-lived, not stored client-side beyond session">

## Code conventions

### AI-specific minimums

These exist because AI tends to write monolithic files and complex functions. Adjust if project has legitimate exceptions (generated code, data files). These numbers live **here** (single source); they are **enforced by the project's linter** — not self-policed — per the `docs/stack-notes.md` AI-minimums→linter-rule mapping (`pm-stack-researcher`'s output; any minimum the linter cannot express is recorded there as convention-only).

- Max source file: 300 lines
- Max function / method: 50 lines
- Cyclomatic complexity: max 10 per function
- No file-level lint suppressions (only line- or function-level with comment)
- New code test coverage: min 80%

